{
  "answer": "**Ghalib's ghazal \"Naqsh faryadi hai kis ki shokhi-e-tehreer ka\" (Diwan-E-Ghalib, ghazal 153) opens with the following first couplet (sher) in transliterated Urdu:**\n\n> Naqsh faryadi hai kis ki shokhi-e-tehreer ka  \n> Kaaghazi hai pairahan har paikar-e-tasveer ka<sup>[1]</sup>\n\n**English translation:**\n\n> Whose playful script does this whole painted world complain of?  \n> Each figure wears the paper robes a petitioner is made of.<sup>[2]</sup>\n\nThis matla (opening couplet) sets the theme of the created world as a complaint against the playful audacity of its divine \"script\" (tehreer), with all figures dressed in paper-like petitioner garb.[^1]: mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/153-naqsh-faryadi-hai-kis-ki-shokhi-e-tehreer-ka/transliteration/#p-325ecd  \n[^2]: mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/153-naqsh-faryadi-hai-kis-ki-shokhi-e-tehreer-ka/translation/#p-0e42b0",
